2 SENATE BILL 296
1 (b) Subject to § 4–1A–03(d)(2) of this title, the Office of the Attorney General shall
2 provide office space and staff for the Ombudsman, with appropriate steps taken to protect
3 the autonomy and independence of the Ombudsman.
4 4–1B–03.
5 (a) Subject to subsections (b) and (c) of this section, the Attorney General shall
6 appoint the Ombudsman.
7 (b) The Ombudsman shall have been admitted to practice law in the State.
8 (c) (1) The Office of the Attorney General shall publish, on its website, notice
9 of the Attorney General’s intent to consider applicants for the Ombudsman position.
10 (2) The notice shall include:
11 (i) application procedures;
12 (ii) criteria for evaluating an applicant’s qualifications; and
13 (iii) procedures for resolving any conflicts of interest.
14 (3) (i) An individual may submit to the Attorney General an application
15 for the Ombudsman position as provided under paragraph (2) of this subsection.
16 (ii) The Office of the Attorney General shall post on its website the
17 names and qualifications of applicants.
18 (d) (1) The term of the Ombudsman is 4 years.
19 (2) At the end of a term, the Ombudsman continues to serve until a
20 successor is appointed and qualifies.
21 (3) An Ombudsman who is appointed after a term begins serves for the
22 remainder of the term until a successor is appointed and qualifies.
23 (e) The Ombudsman shall be a full–time State employee.
24 (f) The Ombudsman is entitled to an annual salary as provided for in the State
25 budget.
26 (G) THE OMBUDSMAN MAY DELEGATE TO A STAFF MEMBER OF THE OFFICE
27 OF THE PUBLIC ACCESS OMBUDSMAN ANY OF THE POWERS AND DUTIES GRANTED
28 TO THE OMBUDSMAN UNDER THIS SUBTITLE.
29 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
30 October 1, 2025.

